{"title_page": "GRLevelX", "text_new": "{{Infobox software\n| name = GRLevelX\n| logo = <!-- Image name is enough. -->\n| logo alt = \n| logo caption = \n| screenshot = GR2Analyst Screenshot (klbb 20080609 0102 01) (2563231232).png\n| screenshot size =\n| screenshot alt = \n| caption = GR2Analyst of a rain storm.\n| collapsible = <!-- Any text here will collapse the screenshot. -->\n| author = Michael Scott Gibson\n| developer = Gibson Ridge Software, LLC\n| released = {{Start date and age|2005|03|df=yes/no}}\n| discontinued = <!-- Set to yes if software is discontinued, otherwise omit. -->\n| ver layout = <!-- simple (default) or stacked -->\n| latest release version = \n| latest release date = <!-- {{Start date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|df=yes/no}} -->\n| latest preview version = \n| latest preview date = <!-- {{Start date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|df=yes/no}} -->\n| repo = <!-- {{URL|example.org}} -->\n| programming language = \n| engine = <!-- or engines -->\n| operating system = \n| platform = \n| included with = \n| size = \n| language = \n| language count = <!-- Number only -->\n| language footnote = \n| genre = \n| license = \n| alexa = \n| website = {{URL|http://www.grlevelx.com}}\n| standard = \n| AsOf = \n}}\n'''GRLevelX''' is a suite of data processing and display programs developed by Gibson Ridge Software, LLC (GRS), to view [[weather radar]] data. It went on the market in March 2005. It comes in three versions, all of which ingest raw data: ''GRLevel2'' and ''GRLevel2 Analyst Edition'' for viewing Level II data of the [[National Weather Service]] (NWS), and ''GRLevel3'' for viewing Level III data. All programs are capable of rendering [[Weather radar#Polarization|dual polarization]] data.\n\nThe software allows the user to view real-time data as well as archive data stored locally or obtained over the internet. It is used by professional forecasters and researchers for general [[precipitation]] analysis as well as severe storm, [[tornado]], and [[tropical cyclone]] monitoring and analysis. Its usage base grew to include many television weathercasters, including by [[The Weather Channel]] severe storms expert [[Gregory S. Forbes|Greg Forbes]], as well as [[Storm chasing|storm chasers]], [[Storm spotting|storm spotters]], [[Emergency management|emergency managers]], weather enthusiasts, private sector meteorologists, and is often used within the NWS, itself.\n\n''GRLevel2 Analyst Edition'' allows the user to take a 3D images of precipitation within clouds, such as in [[supercell]] [[thunderstorm]]s. It's integrated algorithms flag possible [[hail]], [[tornado vortex signature]]s (TVSs), and [[mesocyclone]]s. \n\nAll GRx applications are written in [[Thread (computer science)|multithreaded]] [[C++]] using the base [[Windows API]]s. Software engineer Michael Scott Gibson wrote the programs.<ref>[http://www.grlevelx.com/about.htm About GRLevelX]</ref>\n\n== Overview ==\n\n''GRLevel2'' is a [[Microsoft Windows|Windows]] viewer for live and archived [[NEXRAD]] Level II data (volumetric reflectivity and velocity data<ref>{{Cite web |url= http://www.unidata.ucar.edu/software/idv/docs/userguide/quickstart/RadarLevelII.html |title= Level II Radar |publisher= [[University Corporation for Atmospheric Research|UCAR]] |date= 2009 |accessdate= 2009-10-23}}</ref>). Base reflectivity, base velocity, storm relative velocity, and spectrum width sweeps for all [[radar]] tilts can be ingested. The display has high speed zooming and panning to allow the user a quickly focus on the area of interest. \n\n''GRLevel2 Analyst Edition'' is an advanced NEXRAD Level II analysis application to produce a high quality [[volumetric display]] and several high resolution reflectivity-derived graphical products in addition to the standard Level II data products. Through [[GIS]] implementation, several University-Doppler Radars, such as Missouri states [[X-Band]] [[Radar]] can be viewed.\n\n''GRLevel3'' is a Windows viewer for live NEXRAD Level III data from the NWS Radar Product Central Collection Dissemination Service (already produced 2D images<ref>{{Cite web |url= http://www.unidata.ucar.edu/software/idv/docs/userguide/quickstart/RadarLevelII.html |title= Level III Radar |publisher= [[University Corporation for Atmospheric Research|UCAR]] |date= 2009 |accessdate= 2009-10-23}}</ref>). In addition to Level III WSR-88D data, GR3 supports [[Terminal Doppler Weather Radar|TDWR]], which is high resolution shorter range radar located at some major airports.\n\nGibson also wrote ''GREarth'', which overlays [[Weather satellite|satellite]] and other data and, like the GRLevelX radar viewers, is customizable with [[Geographic information system|GIS]] layers.<ref>[http://www.grlevelx.com/manuals/grearth/ GREarth User Guide]</ref>\n\n=== Algorithms ===\n{{Main|Weather radar|Convective storm detection#Radar{{!}}Convective storm detection by radar}}\n''GR2Analyst'' contains [[algorithm]]s flagging certain features in the [[reflectivity]] data. In reflectivities, ''GR2'' extract the height above ground of the highest elevation where they are greater than 18 dBZ (echo tops), the [[vertically integrated liquid]] water content of clouds (VIL) and the VIL divided by the Echo tops which is an indicator of possible large hail. Further algorithm use environmental information about of {{convert|0|C}} and {{convert|-20|C}} heights, inputted by the user, to output a hail algorithm size. The algorithm uses any temp/height data within 48 hours of the volume scan time. If no recent data is found, it defaults to {{convert|10000|ft}} and {{convert|20000|ft}} for the heights.\n\nThe results are displayed with a high resolution of {{convert|1|km}} x 1 \u00b0 x {{convert|230|km}} grid with 256 data levels. There is an automatic extraction of the storm motion which is integrated in the algorithms for corrections.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.grlevelx.com/manuals/ Manuals]\n* [http://www.erh.noaa.gov/box/glossary.htm Meteorology dictionary] (NWS)\n\n[[Category:Graphic software in meteorology]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox software\n| name = GRLevelX\n| logo = <!-- Image name is enough. -->\n| logo alt = \n| logo caption = \n| screenshot = GR2Analyst Screenshot (klbb 20080609 0102 01) (2563231232).png\n| screenshot size =\n| screenshot alt = \n| caption = GR2Analyst of a rain storm.\n| collapsible = <!-- Any text here will collapse the screenshot. -->\n| author = \n| developer = Gibson Ridge Software, LLC\n| released = {{Start date and age|2005|03|df=yes/no}}\n| discontinued = <!-- Set to yes if software is discontinued, otherwise omit. -->\n| ver layout = <!-- simple (default) or stacked -->\n| latest release version = \n| latest release date = <!-- {{Start date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|df=yes/no}} -->\n| latest preview version = \n| latest preview date = <!-- {{Start date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|df=yes/no}} -->\n| repo = <!-- {{URL|example.org}} -->\n| programming language = \n| engine = <!-- or engines -->\n| operating system = \n| platform = \n| included with = \n| size = \n| language = \n| language count = <!-- Number only -->\n| language footnote = \n| genre = \n| license = \n| alexa = \n| website = {{URL|http://www.grlevelx.com}}\n| standard = \n| AsOf = \n}}\n'''GRLevelX''' is a suite of data processing and display programs developed by Gibson Ridge Software, LLC (GRS), to view [[weather radar]] data. It went on the market in March 2005. It comes in three versions, all of which ingest raw data: ''GRLevel2'' and ''GRLevel2 Analyst Edition'' for viewing Level II data of the [[National Weather Service]] (NWS), and ''GRLevel3'' for viewing Level III data. All programs are capable of rendering [[Weather radar#Polarization|dual polarization]] data.\n\nThe software allows the user to view real-time data as well as archive data stored locally or obtained over the internet. It is used by professional forecasters and researchers for general [[precipitation]] analysis as well as severe storm, [[tornado]], and [[tropical cyclone]] monitoring and analysis. Its usage base grew to include many television weathercasters, including by [[The Weather Channel]] severe storms expert [[Gregory S. Forbes|Greg Forbes]], as well as [[Storm chasing|storm chasers]], [[Storm spotting|storm spotters]], [[Emergency management|emergency managers]], weather enthusiasts, private sector meteorologists, and is often used within the NWS, itself.\n\n''GRLevel2 Analyst Edition'' allows the user to take a 3D images of precipitation within clouds, such as in [[supercell]] [[thunderstorm]]s. It's integrated algorithms flag possible [[hail]], [[tornado vortex signature]]s (TVSs), and [[mesocyclone]]s. \n\nAll GRx applications are written in [[Thread (computer science)|multithreaded]] [[C++]] using the base [[Windows API]]s. Software engineer Michael Scott Gibson wrote the programs.<ref>[http://www.grlevelx.com/about.htm About GRLevelX]</ref>\n\n== Overview ==\n\n''GRLevel2'' is a [[Microsoft Windows|Windows]] viewer for live and archived [[NEXRAD]] Level II data (volumetric reflectivity and velocity data<ref>{{Cite web |url= http://www.unidata.ucar.edu/software/idv/docs/userguide/quickstart/RadarLevelII.html |title= Level II Radar |publisher= [[University Corporation for Atmospheric Research|UCAR]] |date= 2009 |accessdate= 2009-10-23}}</ref>). Base reflectivity, base velocity, storm relative velocity, and spectrum width sweeps for all [[radar]] tilts can be ingested. The display has high speed zooming and panning to allow the user a quickly focus on the area of interest. \n\n''GRLevel2 Analyst Edition'' is an advanced NEXRAD Level II analysis application to produce a high quality [[volumetric display]] and several high resolution reflectivity-derived graphical products in addition to the standard Level II data products. Through [[GIS]] implementation, several University-Doppler Radars, such as Missouri states [[X-Band]] [[Radar]] can be viewed.\n\n''GRLevel3'' is a Windows viewer for live NEXRAD Level III data from the NWS Radar Product Central Collection Dissemination Service (already produced 2D images<ref>{{Cite web |url= http://www.unidata.ucar.edu/software/idv/docs/userguide/quickstart/RadarLevelII.html |title= Level III Radar |publisher= [[University Corporation for Atmospheric Research|UCAR]] |date= 2009 |accessdate= 2009-10-23}}</ref>). In addition to Level III WSR-88D data, GR3 supports [[Terminal Doppler Weather Radar|TDWR]], which is high resolution shorter range radar located at some major airports.\n\nGibson also wrote ''GREarth'', which overlays [[Weather satellite|satellite]] and other data and, like the GRLevelX radar viewers, is customizable with [[Geographic information system|GIS]] layers.<ref>[http://www.grlevelx.com/manuals/grearth/ GREarth User Guide]</ref>\n\n=== Algorithms ===\n{{Main|Weather radar|Convective storm detection#Radar{{!}}Convective storm detection by radar}}\n''GR2Analyst'' contains [[algorithm]]s flagging certain features in the [[reflectivity]] data. In reflectivities, ''GR2'' extract the height above ground of the highest elevation where they are greater than 18 dBZ (echo tops), the [[vertically integrated liquid]] water content of clouds (VIL) and the VIL divided by the Echo tops which is an indicator of possible large hail. Further algorithm use environmental information about of {{convert|0|C}} and {{convert|-20|C}} heights, inputted by the user, to output a hail algorithm size. The algorithm uses any temp/height data within 48 hours of the volume scan time. If no recent data is found, it defaults to {{convert|10000|ft}} and {{convert|20000|ft}} for the heights.\n\nThe results are displayed with a high resolution of {{convert|1|km}} x 1 \u00b0 x {{convert|230|km}} grid with 256 data levels. There is an automatic extraction of the storm motion which is integrated in the algorithms for corrections.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.grlevelx.com/manuals/ Manuals]\n* [http://www.erh.noaa.gov/box/glossary.htm Meteorology dictionary] (NWS)\n\n[[Category:Graphic software in meteorology]]\n", "name_user": "Pierre cb", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/GRLevelX"}
{"title_page": "Doug Harris (athlete)", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2014}}\n{{Use New Zealand English|date=August 2014}}\n{{Infobox sportsperson\n| name             = Doug Harris\n| image            = \n| image_size       = \n| alt              = \n| caption          = \n| birth_name       = Douglas Mostyn Harris\n| birth_date       = {{Birth date|1919|06|15|df=yes}}\n| birth_place      =\n| death_date       = {{Death date and age|1996|06|17|1919|06|15|df=yes}}\n| death_place      = \n| spouse           = \n| country          = New Zealand\n| sport            = [[Track and field]]\n| nationals        = 440 yards champion (1945, 1946, 1947)<br>880 yards champion (1946, 1947)\n}}\n'''Douglas Mostyn Harris ''' (15 June 1919 \u2013 17 June 1996) was a [[New Zealand]] runner who competed at the [[Athletics at the 1948 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's 800 metres|1948 Olympics]] and the [[1950 British Empire Games]].<ref name=\"SR profile\">{{Cite sports-reference | Doug Harris | https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/ha/doug-harris-2.html | 21 September 2018 }}</ref>\n\nHarris won five New Zealand national athletics titles: the 440 yards in 1945, 1946, and 1947; and the 880 yards in 1946 and 1947.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.anzrankings.org.nz/userfiles/file/National_Champions.pdf |title=National champions 1887\u20132016 |date=December 2016|publisher=Athletics New Zealand |accessdate=15 January 2019 | first=Stephen | last=Hollings}}</ref>\n\nHarris died on 17 June 1996, and he was buried at [[H\u0101wera]] Cemetery.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://public.stdc.govt.nz/cemeteries/DetailList.aspx?K=6820 |title=Cemetery details |publisher=South Taranaki District Council |accessdate=15 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{1948 New Zealand Olympic team}}\n{{1950 New Zealand British Empire Games team}}\n{{Footer New Zealand NC 400 m men}}\n{{Footer New Zealand NC 800 m men}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Harris, Doug}}\n[[Category:1919 births]]\n[[Category:1996 deaths]]\n[[Category:New Zealand male middle-distance runners]]\n[[Category:Athletes (track and field) at the 1948 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Olympic athletes of New Zealand]]\n[[Category:Athletes (track and field) at the 1950 British Empire Games]]\n[[Category:Commonwealth Games competitors for New Zealand]]\n[[Category:Burials at Hawera Cemetery]]\n\n\n{{NewZealand-athletics-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2014}}\n{{Use New Zealand English|date=August 2014}}\n{{Infobox sportsperson\n| name             = Doug Harris\n| image            = \n| image_size       = \n| alt              = \n| caption          = \n| birth_name       = Douglas Mostyn Harris\n| birth_date       = {{Birth date|1919|06|15|df=yes}}\n| birth_place      =\n| death_date       = {{Death date and age|1996|06|17|1919|06|15|df=yes}}\n| death_place      = \n| spouse           = \n| country          = New Zealand\n| sport            = [[Track and field]]\n| nationals        = 440 yards champion (1945, 1946, 1947)<br>880 yards champion (1946, 1947)\n}}\n'''Douglas Mostyn Harris ''' (15 June 1919 \u2013 17 June 1996) was a [[New Zealand]] runner who competed at the [[Athletics at the 1948 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's 800 metres|1948 Olympics]] and the [[1950 British Empire Games]].<ref name=\"SR profile\">{{Cite sports-reference | Doug Harris | https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/ha/doug-harris-2.html | 21 September 2018 }}</ref>\n\nHarris won five New Zealand national athletics titles: the 440 yards in 1945, 1946, and 1947; and the 880 yards in 1946 and 1947.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.anzrankings.org.nz/userfiles/file/National_Champions.pdf |title=National champions 1887\u20132016 |date=December 2016|publisher=Athletics New Zealand |accessdate=15 January 2019 | first=Stephen | last=Hollings}}</ref>\n\nHarris died on 17 June 1996, and he was buried at [[Hawera]] Cemetery.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://public.stdc.govt.nz/cemeteries/DetailList.aspx?K=6820 |title=Cemetery details |publisher=South Taranaki District Council |accessdate=15 January 2019}}</ref>\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{1948 New Zealand Olympic team}}\n{{1950 New Zealand British Empire Games team}}\n{{Footer New Zealand NC 400 m men}}\n{{Footer New Zealand NC 800 m men}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Harris, Doug}}\n[[Category:1919 births]]\n[[Category:1996 deaths]]\n[[Category:New Zealand male middle-distance runners]]\n[[Category:Athletes (track and field) at the 1948 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Olympic athletes of New Zealand]]\n[[Category:Athletes (track and field) at the 1950 British Empire Games]]\n[[Category:Commonwealth Games competitors for New Zealand]]\n[[Category:Burials at Hawera Cemetery]]\n\n\n{{NewZealand-athletics-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Onco p53", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up, replaced: Hawera \u2192 H\u0101wera (2) as perWikipedia:Naming_conventions_(New_Zealand)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Doug_Harris_(athlete)"}
{"title_page": "Sanguis Venenatus", "text_new": "{{coi|date=March 2020}}\n{{short description|Elegy for strings by Andrew March in memory of haemophiliacs who lost their lives due to tainted blood.}}\n{{italic title}}\n\n{{Infobox musical composition\n| name                = ''Sanguis Venenatus''\n| translation         = Tainted blood\n| image               = \n| alt                 = \n| caption             = \n| composer            = [[Andrew March]]\n| catalogue           = \n| period              = [[Contemporary classical music]]\n| genre               = [[String orchestra#repertoire|Music for strings]]\n| composed            = {{start date|2009}}\n| premiere_date       = {{Start date|2010|03|20|df=y}} \n| premiere_location   = [[Todmorden]], [[West Yorkshire]]\n| premiere_conductor  = Nick Concannon Hodges\n| Premiere_performers = Todmorden Orchestra\n| publisher           = \n| published           = \n| first_recording     = {{Start date|2011|07|09|df=y}} Reduta Hall, [[Olomouc]], [[Czech Republic]]\n| form                =  [[Ternary form]]\n| duration            = {{Duration|m=5|s=30}}\n| scoring             = [[String orchestra]]\n| misc                = Written in memory of haemophiliacs who lost their lives due to contaminated blood\n}}\n\n'''''Sanguis Venenatus''''' is an elegy for strings by English composer [[Andrew March]] written in memory of [[haemophiliac]]s (and others) affected by the [[United Kingdom tainted blood scandal|Tainted Blood Scandal]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Thursday \u2013 Verity Sharp, Late Junction \u2013 BBC Radio 3|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b06g6456|website=BBC}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Sanguis Venenatus \u2013 Andrew March & Moravian Philharmonic Strings Song \u2013 BBC Music|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180802015204/https://www.bbc.co.uk/music/tracks/n3x4nm|website=BBC}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Composers \u2013 Alliance Publications, Inc.|url=http://www.apimusic.org/march-andrew-b.1973.html|website=www.apimusic.org|language=en}}</ref>{{cite news |last=Rosenberg |first=Donald |date=March 2013 |title=Sounds of America |url=https://reader.exacteditions.com/issues/34724/page/9|website=reader.exacteditions.com |work=Gramophone |location=UK |access-date=2020-04-19|quote=''Slow, aching lines and mild dissonances also inhabit Andrew March\u2032s intensely felt \u2033Sanguis venenatus\u2033.''}}<ref name=\"Todmorden1\">{{cite web|title=Reviews \u2013 Todmorden Orchestra|url=http://www.todmordenorchestra.org.uk/reviews/|website=Todmorden Orchestra}}</ref><ref>{{cite archive |first= |last= |item = Sanguis Venenatus |item-url =https://rcm.koha-ptfs.co.uk/cgi-bin/koha/opac-detail.pl?biblionumber=249942 |type = Audio CD |item-id = |date = 2012 |page= |pages= |fonds = |series = NV5895 Navona Records |collection = In Dimensions : works for string orchestra|repository = RCM Library Catalogue|institution = Royal College of Music |location = London |oclc= |accession= |ref=CD11802}}</ref> The elegy was included in a service on 30 March, 2011 at [[Westminster Abbey]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.westminster-abbey.org/media/4247/chronically-sick-disabled-persons-act-service.pdf |title=A service to mark the 40th anniversay of the coming into effect of the Chronically Sick and Disabled Persons Act (1970) |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=30 March 2011 |website= |publisher=Westminster Abbey |access-date=2020-04-18 |quote=}}</ref> to commemorate the 40th anniversary of the enactment of the UK legislation&nbsp;\u2013&nbsp;the Chronically Sick and Disabled Persons Act (1970). ''Sanguis Venenatus'' was dedicated to the late [[Alf Morris|Lord Morris of Manchester]], to recognise his long\u2013standing support and advocacy for persons with haemophilia.<ref>{{cite web|title=Dimensions&nbsp;\u2013&nbsp;Works for String Orchestra|url=https://www.eclassical.com/shop/17115/art66/4717266-4e7070-0896931000956.pdf|website=EClassical.com|publisher=Navona Records}}</ref> \n\n==Composition==\nIn 2009, Andrew March completed a cycle of 10 string quartets based on the characteristics of [[diurnal]] [[birds of prey]]. The fifth piece, entitled ''Elegy for an Unsuspecting [[Red phalarope|Phalarope]]'' was inspired by the image of a huge [[Common buzzard|buzzard]] snatching a small grey [[Wader|wading bird]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Dimensions \u2013 Works for String Orchestra|url=https://www.eclassical.com/shop/17115/art66/4717266-4e7070-0896931000956.pdf|website=EClassical.com|publisher=Navona Records}}</ref> The photograph, which appeared in [[The Times]], was taken by two birdwatchers, Paul Freestone and Tim Twiggs at [[St Gothian Sands]] in [[Cornwall]].<ref>{{cite news |last=de Bruxelles|first=Simon |date=16 January 2009 |title=Horrified twitchers watch as starving buzzard kills rare phalarope |url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/horrified-twitchers-watch-as-starving-buzzard-kills-rare-phalarope-53hkjvdddgc |work=The Times |location=London |access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=|first= |date=16 January 2009 |title=Buzzard kills rare visitor to British shores |url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/gallery/2009/jan/16/wildlife-cornwall |work=The Guardian |location=London |access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref> This image was used by March as a poignant metaphor for the disaster which befell thousands of haemophiliacs through [[Contaminated blood scandal in the United Kingdom|contaminated blood products]] with which they were treated.<ref name=\"Todmorden1\" />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Works about contaminated haemophilia blood products]]\n[[Category:Music with dedications]]\n[[Category:Funerary and memorial compositions]]\n\n{{Music-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{coi|date=March 2020}}\n{{short description|Elegy for strings by Andrew March in memory of haemophiliacs who lost their lives due to tainted blood.}}\n{{italic title}}\n\n{{Infobox musical composition\n| name                = ''Sanguis Venenatus''\n| translation         = Tainted blood\n| image               = \n| alt                 = \n| caption             = \n| composer            = [[Andrew March]]\n| catalogue           = \n| period              = [[Contemporary classical music]]\n| genre               = [[String orchestra#repertoire|Music for strings]]\n| composed            = {{start date|2009}}\n| premiere_date       = {{Start date|2010|03|20|df=y}} \n| premiere_location   = [[Todmorden]], [[West Yorkshire]]\n| premiere_conductor  = Nick Concannon Hodges\n| Premiere_performers = Todmorden Orchestra\n| publisher           = \n| published           = \n| first_recording     = {{Start date|2011|07|09|df=y}} Reduta Hall, [[Olomouc]], [[Czech Republic]]\n| form                =  [[Ternary form]]\n| duration            = {{Duration|m=5|s=30}}\n| scoring             = [[String orchestra]]\n| misc                = Written in memory of haemophiliacs who lost their lives due to contaminated blood\n}}\n\n'''''Sanguis Venenatus''''' is an elegy for strings by English composer [[Andrew March]] written in memory of [[haemophiliac]]s (and others) affected by the [[United Kingdom tainted blood scandal|Tainted Blood Scandal]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Thursday \u2013 Verity Sharp, Late Junction \u2013 BBC Radio 3|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b06g6456|website=BBC}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Sanguis Venenatus \u2013 Andrew March & Moravian Philharmonic Strings Song \u2013 BBC Music|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180802015204/https://www.bbc.co.uk/music/tracks/n3x4nm|website=BBC}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Composers \u2013 Alliance Publications, Inc.|url=http://www.apimusic.org/march-andrew-b.1973.html|website=www.apimusic.org|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Gramophone \u2013 March 2013|url=https://reader.exacteditions.com/issues/34724/page/9|website=reader.exacteditions.com}}</ref><ref name=\"Todmorden1\">{{cite web|title=Reviews \u2013 Todmorden Orchestra|url=http://www.todmordenorchestra.org.uk/reviews/|website=Todmorden Orchestra}}</ref><ref>{{cite archive |first= |last= |item = Sanguis Venenatus |item-url =https://rcm.koha-ptfs.co.uk/cgi-bin/koha/opac-detail.pl?biblionumber=249942 |type = Audio CD |item-id = |date = 2012 |page= |pages= |fonds = |series = NV5895 Navona Records |collection = In Dimensions : works for string orchestra|repository = RCM Library Catalogue|institution = Royal College of Music |location = London |oclc= |accession= |ref=CD11802}}</ref> The elegy was included in a service on 30 March, 2011 at [[Westminster Abbey]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.westminster-abbey.org/media/4247/chronically-sick-disabled-persons-act-service.pdf |title=A service to mark the 40th anniversay of the coming into effect of the Chronically Sick and Disabled Persons Act (1970) |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=30 March 2011 |website= |publisher=Westminster Abbey |access-date=2020-04-18 |quote=}}</ref> to commemorate the 40th anniversary of the enactment of the UK legislation&nbsp;\u2013&nbsp;the Chronically Sick and Disabled Persons Act (1970). ''Sanguis Venenatus'' was dedicated to the late [[Alf Morris|Lord Morris of Manchester]], to recognise his long\u2013standing support and advocacy for persons with haemophilia.<ref>{{cite web|title=Dimensions&nbsp;\u2013&nbsp;Works for String Orchestra|url=https://www.eclassical.com/shop/17115/art66/4717266-4e7070-0896931000956.pdf|website=EClassical.com|publisher=Navona Records}}</ref> \n\n==Composition==\nIn 2009, Andrew March completed a cycle of 10 string quartets based on the characteristics of [[diurnal]] [[birds of prey]]. The fifth piece, entitled ''Elegy for an Unsuspecting [[Red phalarope|Phalarope]]'' was inspired by the image of a huge [[Common buzzard|buzzard]] snatching a small grey [[Wader|wading bird]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Dimensions \u2013 Works for String Orchestra|url=https://www.eclassical.com/shop/17115/art66/4717266-4e7070-0896931000956.pdf|website=EClassical.com|publisher=Navona Records}}</ref> The photograph, which appeared in [[The Times]], was taken by two birdwatchers, Paul Freestone and Tim Twiggs at [[St Gothian Sands]] in [[Cornwall]].<ref>{{cite news |last=de Bruxelles|first=Simon |date=16 January 2009 |title=Horrified twitchers watch as starving buzzard kills rare phalarope |url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/horrified-twitchers-watch-as-starving-buzzard-kills-rare-phalarope-53hkjvdddgc |work=The Times |location=London |access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=|first= |date=16 January 2009 |title=Buzzard kills rare visitor to British shores |url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/gallery/2009/jan/16/wildlife-cornwall |work=The Guardian |location=London |access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref> This image was used by March as a poignant metaphor for the disaster which befell thousands of haemophiliacs through [[Contaminated blood scandal in the United Kingdom|contaminated blood products]] with which they were treated.<ref name=\"Todmorden1\" />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Works about contaminated haemophilia blood products]]\n[[Category:Music with dedications]]\n[[Category:Funerary and memorial compositions]]\n\n{{Music-stub}}\n", "name_user": "SpookiePuppy", "label": "safe", "comment": "Lead Section: altering Gramophone reference to be a \"cite news\"", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sanguis_Venenatus"}
